              "value": "destroyed"
            },
            {
              "rowId": 141,
              "keyParts": [
                141,
                "p6",
                "verse",
                "v23",
                "note",
                "f"
              ],
              "value": "tn Heb “wiped away” (cf. NRSV “blotted out”)."
            },
            {
              "rowId": 142,
              "keyParts": [
                142,
                "p6",
                "verse",
                "v23",
                "content"
              ],
              "value": "every living thing that was on the surface of the ground, including people, animals, creatures that creep along the ground, and birds of the sky."
            },
            {
              "rowId": 143,
              "keyParts": [
                143,
                "p6",
                "verse",
                "v23",
                "note",
                "f"
              ],
              "value": "tn Heb “from man to animal to creeping thing and to the bird of the sky.”"
            },
            {
              "rowId": 144,
              "keyParts": [
                144,
                "p6",
                "verse",
                "v23",
                "content"
              ],
              "value": "They were wiped off the earth. Only Noah and those who were with him in the ark survived."
            },
            {
              "rowId": 145,
              "keyParts": [
                145,
                "p6",
                "verse",
                "v23",
                "note",
                "f"
              ],
              "value": "tn The Hebrew verb שָׁאָר (sha’ar) means “to be left over; to survive” in the Niphal verb stem. It is the word used in later biblical texts for the remnant that escapes judgment. See G. F. Hasel, “Semantic Values of Derivatives of the Hebrew Root só’r,” AUSS 11 (1973): 152-69."
            },
            {
              "rowId": 146,
              "keyParts": [
                "v023_NET_GEN_007",
                146,
                "p6",
                "verse",
                "v23",
                "plain_text"
              ],
              "value": "23 So the Lord destroyed every living thing that was on the surface of the ground, including people, animals, creatures that creep along the ground, and birds of the sky. They were wiped off the earth. Only Noah and those who were with him in the ark survived."
            },
            {
              "rowId": 147,
              "keyParts": [
                147,
                "p6",
                "verse",
                "v24",
                "label"
              ],
              "value": "24"
            },
            {
              "rowId": 148,
              "keyParts": [
                148,
                "p6",
                "verse",
                "v24",
                "content"
              ],
              "value": "The waters prevailed over"
            },
            {
              "rowId": 149,
              "keyParts": [
                149,
                "p6",
                "verse",
                "v24",
                "note",
                "f"
              ],
              "value": "sn The Hebrew verb translated “prevailed over” suggests that the waters were stronger than the earth. The earth and everything in it were no match for the return of the chaotic deep."
            },
            {
              "rowId": 150,
              "keyParts": [
                150,
                "p6",
                "verse",
                "v24",
                "content"
              ],
              "value": "the earth for 150 days."
            },
